
# Prompt Engineering Best Practices

A general reference for writing reliable, production-grade prompts. These
principles are distilled from patterns that hold up across domains — they
assume nothing about the specific task. Adapt the examples; keep the structure.

---

## Set up the frame

### 1. Open with a clear role and operating mode
State who the model is and how it should behave before giving it work. A role
("you are an expert editor", "you operate as an automated data-processing
system") primes tone, depth, and judgment, and reduces hedging on tasks the
model is allowed to just do.

### 2. Define every input explicitly
List the variables the prompt depends on and label them. The model should never
have to guess what a value represents or where it comes from. Ambiguous inputs
are the most common source of inconsistent output across runs.

### 3. Establish precedence when rules can conflict
If a prompt pulls from multiple sources (a base instruction set plus a style
guide, a reference file, retrieved data), say which one wins in a disagreement.
Without an explicit hierarchy the model resolves conflicts inconsistently.
Example: "Where the reference file and these instructions disagree, these
instructions win."

---

## Make it accurate

### 4. Ground factual claims in retrieved data
The single largest reliability gain: forbid the model from writing facts from
memory and require that every figure, name, date, or claim trace to something
obtained during the run. State it plainly — "if a tool did not return it, you do
not write it" — and repeat that it applies everywhere, not just in one section.

### 5. Default to omission over fabrication
Pair grounding with an explicit fallback for missing data: leave it out and flag
the gap, rather than filling it with a plausible guess. Models will invent to
satisfy a format; an instruction to omit gives them permission not to.

### 6. Prefer self-contained references over context-dependent ones
For any output that will be read later or reused, ban references that silently
expire — "yesterday", "the current version", "recently". Require absolute,
self-anchoring phrasing (a specific date, a named version). This keeps content
correct after the moment it was generated.

---

## Structure the work

### 7. Decompose the task into ordered, numbered steps
Break a complex job into discrete phases (gather, analyze, draft, check) and
number them. Sequencing prevents the model from skipping ahead — for instance,
writing before it has gathered what it needs. Each step should have one clear
job.

### 8. Add a planning or anchor step before action
Have the model write out key reference state first — a plan, the relevant
constraints, the facts it just established — before it produces the deliverable.
This externalizes reasoning the model would otherwise do implicitly and catch
errors early. It works even when the "plan" is just a few lines it writes for
its own use.

### 9. Make conditional logic explicit
Spell out branches and routing as clear "if X, do Y; otherwise do Z" rules
rather than leaving them implied. State when a step should be skipped entirely.
Ambiguous conditionals are where models improvise, so name the path for each
case the prompt actually expects.

---

## Control the output

### 10. Preserve existing structure and voice when editing
When the task modifies existing content rather than creating it fresh, instruct
the model to mirror the original's format and rhythm — lists stay lists, short
paragraphs stay short, tables stay tables. Models tend to "improve" structure
into a uniform block unless told to match what's there.

### 11. Specify the output format with a template
Give an exact skeleton of the expected output, including labels and the order of
sections. A concrete template removes formatting guesswork and makes results
easy to parse or validate downstream. Be explicit about formatting that breaks
your pipeline (e.g., "plain text only, no Markdown bold").

### 12. Bound scope and length
Put numeric limits on the work: target word counts, a maximum number of items,
"one example per source". Caps prevent runaway output and stop the model from
padding. Tie the count to something real where you can — e.g., the number of
edits equals the number of problems found, not an arbitrary quota.

---

## Enforce quality

### 13. Build a mandatory self-audit checklist
Before the final answer, have the model re-read its own draft against a short
checklist and fix anything that fails. List the specific checks (grounding,
format, banned language, scope). A self-review pass catches a meaningful share
of errors the first draft introduces, at low cost.

### 14. Give negative examples, not just positive instructions
Tell the model what to avoid, concretely. This works on two levels:
- Words and phrases — a banned list of clichés, filler, and tells specific to
  your context.
- Structural patterns — habits that read as machine-written even when no banned
  word appears (e.g., reflexive three-item lists, restating a point right after
  making it, empty hedging like "it is worth noting", opening with "Overall").
Naming the anti-pattern is more effective than asking for "natural" writing.

---

## Handle the edges

### 15. Define failure modes and a completion contract
Say what to do when the task can't be completed normally: what to output if no
usable data was found, and a requirement to always return a valid, non-empty
response. Specify an exact failure string if downstream systems need to detect
it. This stops the model from either giving up silently or fabricating to avoid
an empty answer.

### 16. Set a tool or effort budget
For agentic prompts, cap the number of tool calls or attempts and say what to do
on failure (change parameters, then fall back to what's verified). A budget
prevents loops and forces the model to prioritize accuracy over exhaustiveness
when it runs low.

---

## Anti-patterns to avoid in your own prompt-writing

These are author-side mistakes — failures in how the prompt is written, separate
from what you tell the model to avoid in its output (principle 14).

- Contradictory rules. "Be thorough but keep it brief" forces the model to pick
  one and guess which. If two goals compete, rank them or give a concrete bound
  ("complete but under 200 words").
- Undefined qualifiers. "Use good judgment", "be professional", "make it
  engaging" push the decision back onto the model without telling it the
  standard. Define the term or give an example of what passes.
- Negation without a replacement. "Don't use a formal tone" leaves an open space
  the model fills unpredictably. Say what to do instead.
- Rule overload. Past a point, every added rule dilutes the others — the model
  can't weight thirty equally-stated constraints. Keep the must-never set small
  and explicit; demote the rest to guidance.
- Burying the critical instruction. If a rule matters most, it shouldn't sit in
  the middle of paragraph nine. Put non-negotiables at the top and restate them
  where they apply.
- Untestable instructions. If you can't check whether a rule was followed by
  looking at the output, the model can't reliably follow it either. Prefer rules
  with an observable result.
- Examples that contradict the instructions. The model trusts examples over
  prose. A sample output that breaks a stated rule trains the behavior you said
  to avoid — keep examples consistent with the spec.
- Effort theater. "Think very hard", "this is extremely important", "do your
  absolute best" add no constraint. Replace them with the specific behavior you
  actually want.
- Wall-of-text prompts. A single unbroken block hides structure and makes rules
  easy to miss. Use sections, ordered steps, and whitespace — the prompt's own
  formatting affects how reliably it's parsed.

---

## Quick checklist

- [ ] Role and operating mode stated
- [ ] Inputs labeled and defined
- [ ] Rule precedence resolved
- [ ] Facts grounded in retrieved data; omit when unverified
- [ ] References are self-contained, not time-relative
- [ ] Task broken into ordered steps with a planning step first
- [ ] Conditionals and skip-conditions explicit
- [ ] Output format and length specified
- [ ] Existing structure preserved on edits
- [ ] Self-audit checklist included
- [ ] Negative examples given (words and structural patterns)
- [ ] Failure mode and completion contract defined
- [ ] Tool/effort budget set (for agentic prompts)
